<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="act">
<PB N="33" REF="40">
<HEAD>ACT III.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE I.</HEAD>
<STAGE>A wild Retreat among &s;tupendous Rocks.&mdash;<HI>CORA</HI>
and her Child, with other Wives and Children
of the Peruvian Warriors, are &s;cattered about the
&s;cene in groups.&mdash;They &s;ing alternately, Stanzas
expre&s;&s;ive of their &s;ituation, with a <HI>CHORUS,</HI>
in which all join.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t Peruvian Woman.</SPEAKER>
<P>ZULUGA, &s;ee&s;t thou nothing yet?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, two Peruvian &s;oldiers, one on the
hill; the other entering the thicket in the vale.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2d Per. Woman.</SPEAKER>
<P>One more has pa&s;s'd.&mdash;He
comes&mdash;but pale and terrified.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>My heart will &s;tart from my bo&s;om.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter a Peruvian Soldier, panting for breath.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wom.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well! joy or death?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sold.</SPEAKER>
<P>The battle is again&s;t us. The King is
wounded, and a pri&s;oner.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wom.</SPEAKER>
<P>De&s;pair and mi&s;ery!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(In a faint voice.)</STAGE>
<P>And Alonzo?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sold.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have not &s;een him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t Wom.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! whither mu&s;t we fly?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2d Wom.</SPEAKER>
<P>Deeper into the fore&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall not move.</P>
<P>Another Peruvian Soldier, <STAGE>(without.)</STAGE> <HI>Victory!
victory!</HI></P>
<STAGE>He enters ha&s;tily.</STAGE>
<P>Rejoice! Rejoice! we are victorious!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="34" REF="41">
<SPEAKER>Wom.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Springing up.)</STAGE>
<P>Welcome! welcome!
thou me&s;&s;enger of joy: but the King!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sold.</SPEAKER>
<P>He leads the brave warriors, who approach.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(The triumphant march of the army is heard at a di&s;tance.&mdash;The
Women and Children join in a &s;train expre&s;&s;ive of anxiety and
exultation.&mdash;The Warriors enter &s;inging the Song of Victory, in
which all join.&mdash;The <HI>KING</HI> and <HI>ROLLA</HI> follow, and are met
with rapturous and affectionate re&s;pect. <HI>CORA,</HI> during this
&s;cene, with her Child in her arms, runs through the ranks &s;earch|ing
and enquiring for <HI>ALONZO.</HI>)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ata.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thanks, thanks, my children! I am well:
believe it; the blood once &s;topp'd, my wound was
nothing. <STAGE>(Cora <HI>at length approaches</HI> Rolla, <HI>who
appears to have been mournfully avoiding her.</HI>)</STAGE>
Where is Alonzo?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Rolla</HI> turns away in &s;ilence.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Falling at the King's feet.)</STAGE>
<P>Give me my
hu&s;band, give this child his father?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ata.</SPEAKER>
<P>I grieve that Alonzo is not here.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hop'd you to find him?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ata.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mo&s;t anxiou&s;ly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ataliba! is he not dead?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ata.</SPEAKER>
<P>No! the Gods will have heard our prayers.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is he not dead, Ataliba?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ata.</SPEAKER>
<P>He lives&mdash;in my heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh King! torture me not thus! &s;peak
out, is this child fatherle&s;s?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ata.</SPEAKER>
<P>Deare&s;t Cora! do not thus da&s;h a&s;ide the
little hope that &s;till remains.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>The little hope! yet &s;till there <HI>is</HI> hope!
Speak to me, Rolla: <HI>you</HI> are the <HI>friend of truth.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alonzo has not been found.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not found! What mean you? will not
<PB N="35" REF="42">
<HI>you,</HI> Rolla, tell me truth? Oh! let me not hear
the thunder rolling at a di&s;tance; let the bolt fall
and cru&s;h my brain at once.&mdash;Say not that he is
not found: &s;ay at once that he is dead.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then &s;hould I &s;ay fal&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>Fal&s;e!</HI> Ble&s;&s;ings on thee for that word!
But &s;natch me from this terrible &s;u&s;pen&s;e. Lift
up thy little hands, my child; perhaps thy igno|rance
may plead better than thy mother's agony.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alonzo is taken pri&s;oner.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pri&s;oner! and by the Spaniards? Pizar|ro's
pri&s;oner? Then is he dead.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ata.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hope better&mdash;the riche&s;t ran&s;om which our
realm can yield, a herald &s;hall this in&s;tant bear.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Per. Wom.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! for Alonzo's ran&s;om&mdash;our
gold, our gems!&mdash;all! all!&mdash;Here, dear Cora,
&mdash;here! here!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(The Peruvian Women eagerly tear off all their
ornaments, and run and take them from their
children, to offer them to <HI>Cora.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ata.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, for Alonzo's ran&s;om they would
give all!&mdash;I thank thee, Father, who ha&s;t given
me &s;uch hearts to rule over!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now one boon more, beloved monarch.
Let me go with the herald.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ata.</SPEAKER>
<P>Remember, Cora, thou art not a wife only,
but a mother too: hazard not your own honour,
and the &s;afety of your infant. Among the&s;e
barbarians the &s;ight of thy youth, thy loveline&s;s,
and innocence, would but rivet fa&s;ter your Alonzo's
chains, and rack his heart with added fears for
thee.&mdash;Wait, Cora, the return of the herald.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Teach me how to live till then.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ata.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now we go to offer to the Gods, thanks
for our victory, and prayers for our Alonzo's
&s;afety.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[March and proce&s;&s;ion&punc; Exeunt omnes.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<PB N="36" REF="43">
<HEAD>SCENE II.</HEAD>
<STAGE>The Wood.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>CORA</HI> and Child.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mild innocence, what will become of
thee?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>ROLLA.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Cora, I attend thy &s;ummons at th' ap|pointed
&s;pot.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh my child, my boy!&mdash;ha&s;t thou &s;till
a father?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Cora, can thy child be fatherle&s;s, while
Rolla lives?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Will he not &s;oon want a mother too?&mdash;For
can&s;t thou think I will &s;urvive Alonzo's
lo&s;s?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes! for his child's &s;ake.&mdash;Yes, as thou
did&s;t love Alonzo, Cora, li&s;ten to Alonzo's friend.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>You bid me li&s;ten to the world.&mdash;Who
was not Alonzo's friend?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>His parting words&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>His parting words! <STAGE>(Wildly.)</STAGE> Oh, &s;peak!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Con&s;igned to me two precious tru&s;ts&mdash;his
ble&s;&s;ing to his &s;on, and a la&s;t reque&s;t to thee.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>His <HI>la&s;t</HI> reque&s;t! his <HI>la&s;t!</HI>&mdash;Oh, name it!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>If I fall, &s;aid he&mdash;(and &s;ad forebodings
&s;hook him while he &s;poke)&mdash;promi&s;e to take my
Cora for thy wife; be thou a father to my child.
&mdash;I&punc; pledged my word to him, and we parted.&mdash;Ob&s;erve
me, Cora, I repeat this only, as my
faith to do &s;o was given to Alonzo&mdash;for my&s;elf,
I neither cheri&s;h claim or hope.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! does my rea&s;on fail me, or what
<PB N="37" REF="44">
is this horrid light that pre&s;&s;es on my brain? Oh,
Alonzo! It may be thou ha&s;t fallen a victim to
thy own guilele&s;s heart&mdash;had&s;t thou been &s;ilent,
had&s;t thou not made a fatal legacy of the&s;e
wretched charms&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Cora! what hateful &s;u&s;picion has po&s;&s;e&s;|&s;ed
thy mind?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes, 'tis clear&mdash;his &s;pirit was en|&s;nar'd;
he was led to the fatal &s;pot, where mortal
valour could not front a ho&s;t of murderers&mdash;He fell
&mdash;in vain did he exclaim for help to Rolla. At a
di&s;tance you look'd on and &s;mil'd&mdash;You could have
&s;aved him&mdash;could&mdash;but did not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, glorious &s;un! can I have de&s;erved
this? Cora, rather bid me &s;trike this &s;word into
my heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>No! live! $ive for love! for that love
thou &s;eeke&s;t; who&s;e blo&s;&s;oms are to &s;hoot from
the bleeding grave of thy betray'd and &s;laughter'd
friend!&mdash;But thou ha&s;t borne to me the <HI>la&s;t words</HI>
of my <HI>Alonzo!</HI> Now hear <HI>mine</HI>&mdash;Sooner &s;hall this
boy draw poi&s;on from this tortured brea&s;t&mdash;&s;ooner
would I link me to the pallid cor&s;e of the meane&s;t
wretch that peri&s;h'd with Alonzo, than he call
Rolla father&mdash;than I call Rolla hu&s;band!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yet call me what I am&mdash;thy friend, thy
protector!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Di&s;tractedly.)</STAGE>
<P>Away! I have no protec|tor
but my God!&mdash;With this child in my arms
will I ha&s;ten to the field of &s;laughter&mdash;There
with the&s;e hands will I turn up to the light every
mangled body&mdash;&s;eeking, howe'er by death disfi|gur'd,
the &s;weet &s;mile of my Alonzo:&mdash;with fear|ful
cries I will &s;hriek out his name till my veins
&s;nap! If the &s;malle&s;t &s;park of life remains, he
<PB N="38" REF="45">
will know the voice of his Cora, open for a mo|ment
his un&s;hrouded eyes, and ble&s;s me with a
la&s;t look: But if we find him not&mdash;Oh! then,
my boy, we will to the Spani&s;h camp&mdash;that look
of thine will win me pa&s;&s;age through a thou&s;and
&s;words&mdash;They too are men. Is there a heart that
could drive back the wife that &s;eeks her bleeding
hu&s;band; or the innocent babe that cries for his
impri&s;on'd father? No, no, my child, every
where we &s;hall be &s;afe. A wretched mother bear|ing
a poor orphan in her arms, has Nature's pa&s;&s;|port
through the world. Yes, yes, my &s;on, we'll
go and &s;eek thy father.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit with the child.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(After a pau&s;e of agitation.)</STAGE>
<P>Could I have
merited one breath of thy reproaches, Cora, I
&s;hould be the wretch&mdash;I think was not formed to
be. HER &s;afety mu&s;t be my pre&s;ent purpo&s;e&mdash;then
to convince her &s;he has wronged me!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Exit.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE III.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">Pizarro's Tent.</HEAD>
<STAGE>PIZARRO, traver&s;ing the &s;cene in gloomy and furious
agitation.</STAGE>
<P>Well, capricious idol, Fortune, be my ruin thy
work and boa&s;t. To my&s;elf I will &s;till be true.&mdash;Yet
ere I fall, grant me thy &s;mile to pro&s;per in one
act of vengeance, and be that &s;mile Alonzo's death.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ELVIRA.</STAGE>
<P>Who's there? who dares intrude? Why does my
guard neglect their duty?</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your guard did what they could&mdash;but they
<PB N="39" REF="46">
knew their du$y better than to enforce authority,
when I refu&s;ed obedience.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>And what is it you de&s;ire?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>To &s;ee how a hero bears misfortune. Thou,
Pizarro, art not now collected&mdash;not thy&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Would&s;t thou I &s;hould rejoice that the
&s;pears of the enemy, led by accurs'd Alonzo, have
pierced the brave&s;t hearts of my followers?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>No!&mdash;I would have thee cold and dark as
the night that follows the departed &s;torm; &s;till and
&s;ullen as the awful pau&s;e that precedes Nature's
convul&s;ion: yet I would have thee feel a&s;&s;ured that
a new morning &s;hall ari&s;e, when the warrior's &s;pi|rit
&s;hall &s;talk forth&mdash;nor fear the future, nor la|ment
the pa&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Woman! Elvira!&mdash;Why had not all my men
hearts like thine?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then would thy brows have this day worn
the crown of Quito.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! hope fails me while that &s;courge of
my life and fame, Alonzo, leads the enemy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pizarro, I am come to probe the hero
farther: not now his courage, but his magnani|mity&mdash;Alonzo
is your pri&s;oner.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>How!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis certain; Valvarde &s;aw him even
now dragged in chains within your camp. I
cho&s;e to bring you the intelligence my&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ble&s;s thee, Elvira, for the news!&mdash;Alonzo
in my power!&mdash;then I am the conqueror&mdash;the
victory is MINE!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pizarro, this is &s;avage and unmanly
triumph. Believe me, you rai&s;e impatience in
my mind to &s;ee the man who&s;e valour, and
who&s;e genius, awe Pizarro; who&s;e misfortunes
<PB N="40" REF="47">
are Pizarro's triumph; who&s;e bondage is P$|zarro's
&s;afety.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Guard!&mdash;<STAGE>(Enter Guard.)</STAGE>&mdash;Drag here the
Spani&s;h pri&s;oner, Alonzo!&mdash;Quick bring the trai|tor
here.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit Guard.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>What &s;hall be his fate?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Death! death! in lingering torments!
protracted to the la&s;t &s;tretch that burning ven|geance
can devi&s;e, and fainting life &s;u&s;tain.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shame on thee! wilt thou have it &s;aid that
the Peruvians found Pizarro&punc; could not conquer till
Alonzo felt that he could murder?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be it &s;aid&mdash;I care not. His fate is &s;ealed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Follow then thy will: but mark me; if
ba&s;ely thou do&s;t &s;hed the blood of this brave youth,
Elvira's lo&s;t to thee for ever.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why this intere&s;t for a &s;tranger? What
is Alonzo's fate to thee?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>His &s;ate!&mdash;nothing!&mdash;thy glory, every
thing!&mdash;Think'&s;t tho$ I could love thee &s;tript of
fame, of honour, and a ju&s;t renown?&mdash;Know me
better.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thou &s;hould&s;t have known ME better.
Thou &s;hould&s;t have known, that, once provoked
to hate, I am for ever fixed in vengeance.&mdash;
<STAGE>(<HI>Alonzo</HI> is brought in, in chains, guarded. <HI>Elvira</HI>
ob&s;erves him with attention and admiration.)</STAGE>&mdash;Wel|come,
welcome, Don Alonzo de Molina; 'tis
long &s;ince we have met: thy mended looks &s;hould
&s;peak a life of rural indolence. How is it that
amid the toils and cares of war thou do&s;t pre&s;erve
the healthful bloom of carele&s;s ea&s;e? Tell me thy
&s;ecret.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thou wilt not profit by it. Whate'er the
toils or cares of war, peace &s;till is <HI>here.</HI></P>
<STAGE>(Putting
his hand to his heart.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="41" REF="48">
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sarca&s;tic boy!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thou art an&s;wered rightly. Why &s;port
with the unfortunate?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>And thou art wedded too, I hear; aye,
and the father of a lovely boy&mdash;the heir, no doubt,
of all his father's loyalty; of all his mother's faith.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>The heir, I tru&s;t, of all his father's &s;corn
of fraud, oppre&s;&s;ion, and hypocri&s;y&mdash;the heir, I
hope, of all his mother's virtue, gentlene&s;s, and
truth&mdash;the heir, I am &s;ure, to all Pizarro's hate.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Really! Now do I feel for this poor or|phan;
for fatherle&s;s to-morrow's &s;un &s;hall &s;ee
that child. Alonzo, thy hours are numbered.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pizarro&mdash;no!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hence&mdash;or dread my anger.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will not hence; nor do I dread thy
anger.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>Generous loveline&s;s! &s;pare thy unavail|ing
pity. Seek not to thwart the tiger with his
prey beneath his fangs.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Audacious rebel! Thou, a renegado from
thy monarch and thy God!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis fal&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Art thou not, tell me, a de&s;erter from
thy country's legions&mdash;and, with vile heathens
leagued, ha&s;t thou not warred again&s;t thy native
land?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>No! De&s;erter I am none! I was not born
among robbers! pirates! murderers!&mdash;When
tho&s;e legions, lured by the abhorred lu&s;t of gold,
and by thy foul ambition urged, forgot the ho|nour
of Ca&s;tilians, and for&s;ook the duties of hu|manity,
THEY de&s;erted ME. I have not warred
again&s;t my native land, but again&s;t tho&s;e who
ha$e u&s;urped its power. The banners of my
<PB N="42" REF="49">
country, when fir&s;t I followed arms beneath them,
were Ju&s;tice, Faith, and Mercy. If the&s;e are
beaten down and trampled under foot&mdash;I have
no country, nor exi&s;ts the power entitled to re|proach
me with revolt.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>The power of judge and puni&s;h thee at
lea&s;t exi&s;ts.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>Where are my judges?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thou would&s;t appeal to the war council?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>If the good Las-Ca&s;as have yet a &s;eat there,
yes; if not, I appeal to Heaven!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>And to impo&s;e upon the folly of Las-Ca&s;as,
what would be the excu&s;es of thy trea&s;on?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>The folly of Las-Ca&s;as!&mdash;Such, doubt|le&s;s,
his mild precepts &s;eem to thy hard-hearted
wi&s;dom!&mdash;O! would I might have lived as I will
die, a &s;harer in the follies of Las-Ca&s;as!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>To him I &s;hould not need to urge the
foul barbarities which drove me from your &s;ide;
but I would gently lead him by the hand through
all the lovely fields of Quito; there, in many a
&s;pot where late was barrenne&s;s and wa&s;te, I
would &s;how him how now the opening blo&s;&s;om,
blade, or per$umed bud, &s;weet ba&s;hful pledges of
delicious harve&s;t, wafting their incen&s;e to the
ripening fun, give chearful promi&s;e to the hope
of indu&s;try. This, I would &s;ay, is my work!
Next I &s;hould tell how hurtful cu&s;toms, and &s;u|per&s;titions
&s;trange and &s;ullen, would often &s;catter
and di&s;may the credulous minds of the&s;e deluded
innocents; and then would I point out to him
where now, in clu&s;tered villages, they live like
brethren, &s;ocial and confiding, while through
the burning day Content &s;its ba&s;king on the cheek
of Toil, till laughing Pa&s;time leads them to the
hour of re&s;t&mdash;this too is mine!&mdash;And prouder
<PB N="43" REF="50">
yet&mdash;at that &s;till pau&s;e between exertion and re|po&s;e,
belonging not to pa&s;time, labour, or to
re&s;t, but unto Him who &s;anctions and ordains
them all, I would &s;how him many an eye, and
many a hand, by gentlene&s;s from error won,
rai&s;ed in pure devotion to the true and only God$
&mdash;this too I could tell him is Alonzo's work!&mdash;Then
would Las-Ca&s;as cla&s;p me in his aged arms;
from his uplifted eyes a tear of gracious thankful|ne&s;s
would fall upon my head, and that one ble&s;&s;ed
drop would be to me at once <HI>this</HI> world's be&s;t proof,
that I had acted rightly <HI>here,</HI> and &s;ure&s;t hope of
my Creator's mercy and reward <HI>hereafter</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Happy, virtuous Alonzo! And thou, Pi|zarro,
would&s;t appal with fear of death a man
who thinks and acts as he does!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Daring, ob&s;tinate enthu&s;ia&s;t! But know
the pious ble&s;&s;ing of thy preceptor's tears does not
await thee here: he has fled like thee&mdash;like thee,
no doubt, to join the foes of Spain. The perilous
trial of the next reward you hope, is nearer than
perhaps you've thought; for, by my country's
wrongs, and by mine own, to-morrow's &s;un &s;hall
&s;ee thy death.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold!&mdash;Pizarro&mdash;hear me!&mdash;If not al|ways
<HI>ju&s;tly,</HI> at lea&s;t act always <HI>greatly.</HI> Name
not thy country's worngs&mdash;'tis plain they have
no &s;hare in thy re&s;entment. Thy fury 'gain&s;t
this youth is private hate, and deadly per&s;onal
revenge; if this be &s;o&mdash;and even now thy de|tected
con&s;cience in that look avows it&mdash;profane
not the name of ju&s;tice or thy country's cau&s;e,
but let him arm, and bid him to the field on equal
terms.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="44" REF="51">
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Officious advocate for trea&s;on&mdash;peace!
&mdash;Bear him hence&mdash;he knows his &s;entence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thy revenge is eager, and I'am thankful for
it&mdash;to me thy ha&s;te is mercy. For thee, &s;weet
pleader in misfortune's cau&s;e, accept my parting
thanks. This camp is not thy proper &s;phere. We it
thou among yo$ <HI>&s;avages,</HI> as they are called, thou'd&s;t
find companions more congenial to thy heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; &s;he &s;hall bear the tidings of thy
death to Cora.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>Inhuman man! that pang at lea&s;t might
have been &s;pared me; but thy malice &s;hall not
&s;hake my con&s;tancy. I go to death&mdash;many &s;hall
ble&s;s, and none will cur&s;e my memory. Thou &s;till
wilt live, and &s;till wilt be&mdash;Pizarro.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit, guarded.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now by the indignant &s;corn that burns upon
my cheek, my &s;oul is &s;hamed and &s;ickened at the
meanne&s;s of thy vengeance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>What has thy romantic folly aimed at?
He is mine enemy, and in my power.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>He is in your power, and therefore is no
more an enemy. Pizarro I demand not of thee
virtue&mdash;I a&s;k not from thee noblene&s;s of mind&mdash;I
require only ju&s;t dealing to the fame thou ha&s;t
acquired; be not the a&s;&s;a&s;&s;in of thine own
renown. How often have you &s;worn that the
&s;acrifice which thy wondrous valour's high
report had won you from &s;ubdued Elvira, was
the proude&s;t triumph of your fame? Thou
knowe&s;t I bear a mind not ca&s;t in the common
mould&mdash;not formed for tame &s;eque&s;tered love&mdash;content
'mid hou&s;ehold cares to prattle to an
idle offspring, and wait the dull delight of an
ob&s;cure lover's kindne&s;s&mdash;no! my heart was
<PB N="45" REF="52">
framed to look up with awe and homage to the
object it adored; my ears to own no mu&s;ic but
the thrilling records of his prai&s;e; my lips to
&s;corn all babbling but the tales of his atchieve|ments;
my brain to turn giddy with delight,
reading the applauding tributes of his monarch's
and his country's gratitude; my every faculty to
throb with tran&s;port, while I heard the &s;houts of
acclamation which announced the coming of my
hero; my whole &s;oul to love him with devotion!
with enthu&s;ia&s;m! to &s;ee no other object&mdash;to own
no other tie&mdash;but to make HIM my WORLD!
Thus to love is at lea&s;t no common weakne&s;s.
&mdash;Pizarro!&mdash;was not &s;uch my love for thee?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>It <HI>was,</HI> Elvira!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then do not make me hateful to my&s;elf,
by tearing off the ma&s;k at once&mdash;baring the
hideous impo&s;ture that has undone me!&mdash;Do
not an act which, howe'er thy pre&s;ent power
may glo&s;s it to the world, will make thee hate|ful
to all future ages&mdash;accur&s;ed and &s;corned by
po&s;terity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;hould po&s;terity applaud my deeds,
think'&s;t thou my mouldering bones would rattle
then with tran&s;port in my tomb?&mdash;This is re|nown
for vifionary boys to dream of&mdash;I under|&s;tand
it not. The fame I value &s;hall uplift my
living e&s;timation&mdash;o'er bear, with popular &s;upport
the envy of my foes&mdash;advance my purpo&s;es, and
aid my power.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Each word thou &s;peake&s;t&mdash;each moment
that I hear thee&mdash;di&s;pels the fatal mi&s;t through
which I've judged thee. Thou man of mighty
name, but little &s;oul, I &s;ee thou wert not born
to feel what genuine fame and glory are&mdash;yes,
prefer the flattery of thy own fleeting day to the
<PB N="46" REF="53">
bright circle of a deathle&s;s name&mdash;yes, prefer
to &s;tare upon the grain of &s;and on which you
trample, to mu&s;ing on the &s;tarred canopy above
thee. Fame, the &s;overeign deity of proud am|bition,
is not to be wor&s;hipped &s;o: who &s;eeks
alone for living homage, &s;tands a mean canva&s;&s;er
in her temple's porch, wooing promi&s;cuou&s;ly
from the fickle breath of every wretch that pa&s;&s;es,
the brittle tribute of his prai&s;e. He dares not
approach the &s;acred altar&mdash;no noble &s;acrifice of
his is placed there, nor ever &s;hall his wor&s;hip'd
image&punc; fix'd above, claim for his memory a glo|rious
immortality.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Elvira, leave me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pizarro, you no longer lover me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is not &s;o, Elvira. But what might I not
&s;u&s;pect&mdash;this wondrous intere&s;t for a &s;tranger!&mdash;Take
back thy reproach.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Pizarro; as yet I am not lo&s;t to
you&mdash;one &s;tring &s;till remains, and binds me to
your fate. Do not I conjure you&mdash;do not for
thine own &s;ake, tear it a&s;under&mdash;&s;hed not Alon|zo's
blood!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>My re&s;olution's fixed.]</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Even though that moment lo&s;t you Elvira
for ever?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Even &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pizarro, if not to honour, if not to hu|manity,
yet li&s;ten to affection; bear &s;ome me|mory
of the &s;acrifices I have made for thy &s;ake.
Have I not for thee quitted my parents, my
friends, my fame, my native land? When
e&s;caping, did I not ri&s;que in ru&s;hing to thy arms
to bury my&s;elf in the bo&s;om of the deep? Have
I not &s;hared all thy perils, heavy &s;torms at &s;ea,
and frightful '&s;capes on &s;hore? Even on this
<PB N="47" REF="54">
dreadful day, amid the route of battle, who re|mained
firm and con&s;tant at Pizarro's &s;ide? Who
pre&s;ented her bo&s;om as his &s;hield to the a&s;&s;ailing
foe?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis truly &s;poken all. In love thou art
thy &s;ex's miracle&mdash;in war the &s;oldier's pattern&mdash;and
therefore my whole heart and half my ac|qui&s;itions
are thy right.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Convince me I po&s;&s;e&s;s the fir&s;t&mdash;I ex|change
all title to the latter, for&mdash;mercy to Alon|zo.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>No more!&mdash;Had I intended to prolong his
doom, each word thou uttere&s;t now would ha&s;ten
on his fate.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alonzo then at morn will die?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Think'&s;t thou you &s;un will &s;et?&mdash;As &s;urely
at his ri&s;ing &s;hall Alonzo die.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then be it done&mdash;the &s;tring is crack'd&mdash;&s;undered
for ever.&mdash;But mark me&mdash;thou ha&s;t
heretofore had cau&s;e, 'tis true, to doubt my re&s;o|lution,
howe'er offended&mdash;but mark me now&mdash;the
lips which, cold and jeering, barbing revenge
with rancorous mockery, can in&s;ult a fallen ene|my,
&s;hall never more receive the pledge of love:
the arm un&s;haken by its bloody purpo&s;e, which
&s;hall a&s;&s;ign to needle&s;s torture the victim who
avows his heart, never more &s;hall pre&s;s the hand
of faith!&mdash;Pizarro, &s;corn not my words&mdash;beware
you &s;light them not!&mdash;I feel how noble are the mo|tives
which now animate my thoughts&mdash;who <HI>could</HI>
not feel as I do, I condemn&mdash;who, feeling &s;o, yet
<HI>would</HI> not act as I SHALL, I de&s;pi&s;e!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>(<HI>After a pau&s;e, looking at her with an af|fected
&s;mile of contempt</HI>) I have heard thee, Elvira,
and know well the <HI>noble</HI> motives which in&s;pire
<PB N="48" REF="55">
thee&mdash;fit advocate in virtue's cau&s;e!&mdash;Believe me,
I pity thy tender feelings for the youth Alonzo!&mdash;He
dies at &s;un-ri&s;e!</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis well! 'tis ju&s;t I &s;hould be humbled&mdash;I
had forgot my&s;elf, and in the cau&s;e of innocence
a&s;&s;umed the tone of virtue. 'Twas fit I &s;hould be
rebuked&mdash;and by Pizarro. Fall, fall, ye few re|luctant
drops of weakne&s;s&mdash;the la&s;t the&s;e eyes
&s;hall ever &s;hed. How a woman can love Pizarro,
thou ha&s;t known too well&mdash;how &s;he can hate,
thou ha&s;t yet to learn. Yes, thou undaunted!
Thou whom yet no mortal hazard has appalled&punc;
Thou, who on Panama's brow did&s;t make alli|ance
with the raving elements, that $ore the &s;ilence
of that horrid night&mdash;when thou did&s;t follow, as
thy pioneer, the cra&s;hing thunder's drift, and &s;talk|ing
o'er the trembling earth, did&s;t plant thy banner
by the red volcano's mouth! Thou, who when
battling on the &s;ea, and thy brave &s;hip was blown
to &s;plinters, wa&s;t &s;een&mdash;as thou did&s;t be&s;tride a
fragment of the &s;moaking wreck&mdash;to wave thy
glittering &s;word above thy head&mdash;as thou would&s;t
defy the world in that extremity!&mdash;Come, fearle&s;s
man&mdash;now meet the la&s;t and felle&s;t peril of thy life
&mdash;meet! and &s;urvive&mdash;an injured woman's fury,
if thou can&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<TRAILER>END OF THE THIRD ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="act">
<PB N="49" REF="56">
<HEAD>ACT. IV.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE I.</HEAD>
<STAGE>A Dungeon in the Rock, near the Spani&s;h Camp.&mdash;<HI>ALONZO</HI>
in Chains.&mdash;A Centinel walking near the
Entrance.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>For the la&s;t time, I have beheld the
&s;hadow'd ocean clo&s;e upon the light.&mdash;For the la&s;t
time, thro' my cleft dungeon's roof, I now be|hold
the quivering lu&s;tre of the &s;tars.&mdash;For the
la&s;t time, O &s;un! <STAGE>(and &s;oon the hour)</STAGE> I &s;hall be|hold
thy ri&s;ing, and thy level beams melting the
pale mi&s;ts of morn to glittering dew-drops.&mdash;Then
comes my death, and in the morning of my day,
I fall, which&mdash;No, Alonzo, date not the life which
thou ha&s;t run, by the mean reck'ning of the hours
and days, which thou ha&s;t breath'd: A life &s;pent
worthily, $$ould be mea&s;ured by a nobler line&mdash;by
deeds&mdash;not years&mdash;Then woud'&s;t thou murmur not
&mdash;but ble&s;s the Providence, which in &s;o &s;hort a
&s;pan, made THEE the in&s;trument of wide and
&s;preading ble&s;&s;ings, to the helple&s;s and oppre&s;s'd!&mdash;Tho'
&s;inking in decrepid age&mdash;HE prematurely
falls, who&s;e memory records no benefit conferred by
him on man: They only have lived long, who
have lived virtuou&s;ly.</P>
</SP>
<PB N="50" REF="57">
<STAGE>Enter a Soldier&mdash;&s;hews the Centinel a Pa&s;&s;port, who
withdraws.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alonzo.</SPEAKER>
<P>What bear you there?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>The&s;e refre&s;hment I was order'd to leave in
your dungeon.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>By whom order'd?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>By the lady Elvira; &s;he will be here her&s;elf
before the dawn.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bear back to her my humble&s;t thanks; and
take thou the refre&s;hments, friend&mdash;I need them
not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have &s;erved under you, Don Alonzo.&mdash;Pardon
my &s;aying, that my heart pities you.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>In Pizarro's camp, to pity the unfortunate,
no doubt requires forgivene&s;s.&mdash;<STAGE>(Looking out)</STAGE> Sure|ly,
even now, thin &s;treaks of glimmering light
&s;teal on the darkne&s;s of the Ea&s;t.&mdash;If &s;o, my life is
but one hour more.&mdash;I will not watch the coming
dawn; but in the darkne&s;s of my cell, my la&s;t
prayer to thee, Power Supreme! &s;hall be for my
wife and child!&mdash;Grant them to dwell in innocence
and peace; grant health and purity of mind&mdash;all
el&s;e his worthle&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Enters the Cavern.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cent.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who's there? an&s;wer quickly! who's
there?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>A Friar, come to vi&s;it your pri&s;oner.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>ROLLA enters, di&s;gui&s;ed as a Monk.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Inform me, friend&mdash;Is not Alonzo, the
Spani&s;h pri&s;oner, confined in this dungeon?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cen.</SPEAKER>
<P>He is.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>I mu&s;t &s;peak with him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="51" REF="58">
<SPEAKER>Cen.</SPEAKER>
<P>You mu&s;t not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>He is my friend.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cen.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not if he were your brother.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>What is to be his fate?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cen.</SPEAKER>
<P>He dies at &s;un-ri&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha!&mdash;then I am come in time.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cen.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ju&s;t&mdash;to witne&s;s his death.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Soldier&mdash;I mu&s;t &s;peak with him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cen.</SPEAKER>
<P>Back,&mdash;back.&mdash;It is impo&s;&s;ible!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do entreat you, but for one moment!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cen.</SPEAKER>
<P>You entreat in vain&mdash;my orders are mo&s;t
&s;trict.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Even now, I &s;aw a me&s;&s;enger go hence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cen.</SPEAKER>
<P>He brought a pa&s;s, which we are all accu&s;|tomed
to obey.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Look on this wedge of ma&s;&s;ive gold&mdash;look
on the&s;e precious gems.&mdash;In thy own land they
will be wealth for thee and thine, beyond they hope
or wi&s;h. Take them&mdash;they are thine.&mdash;Let me
but pa&s;s one minute with Alonzo.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cen.</SPEAKER>
<P>Away!&mdash;woud'&s;t thou corrupt me?&mdash;Me!
&mdash;an old Ca&s;tilian&mdash;I know my duty better.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Soldier!&mdash;ha&s;t thou a wife?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cen.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha&s;t thou children?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cen.</SPEAKER>
<P>Four&mdash;hone&s;t, lively boys.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Where did'&s;t thou leave them?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cen.</SPEAKER>
<P>In my native village&mdash;even in the cot where
my&s;elf was born.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do'&s;t thou love thy children and thy wife?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cen.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do I love them! God knows my heart,&mdash;I
do.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Soldier! imagine thou wer't doom'd to die
a cruel death in this &s;trange land&mdash;What would be
thy la&s;t reque&s;t?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="52" REF="59">
<SPEAKER>Cen.</SPEAKER>
<P>That &s;ome of my comrades &s;hould carry
my dying ble&s;&s;ing to my wife and children.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! but if that comrade was at thy pri|&s;on
gate&mdash;and &s;hould there be told&mdash;thy fellow
&s;oldier dies at &s;un-ri&s;e,&mdash;yet thou &s;halt not for a
moment &s;ee him&mdash;nor &s;halt thou bear his dying
ble&s;&s;ing to his poor children or his wretched wife,
&mdash;what woud'&s;t thou think of him, who thus cou'd
drive thy comrade from the door?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cen.</SPEAKER>
<P>How!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alonzo has a wife and child&mdash;I am come
but to receive for <HI>her,</HI> and for her <HI>babe,</HI> the la&s;t
ble&s;&s;ing of my friend.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cen.</SPEAKER>
<P>Go in&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(Retires.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! holy Nature! thou do'&s;t never plead
in vain.&mdash;There is not, of our earth, a creature
bearing form, and life, human or &s;avage&mdash;native
of the fore&s;t wild, or giddy air&mdash;around who&s;e
parent bo&s;om, thou ha&s;t not a cord entwined of
power to tie them to their offspring's claims, and
at thy will to draw them back to thee. On iron
pennons borne&mdash;the blood-&s;tain'd vulture, cleaves
the &s;torm&mdash;yet, is the plumage clo&s;e&s;t to her heart,
&s;oft as the Cygnet's down, and o'er her un&s;hell'd
brood, the murmuring ring-dove &s;its not more
gently!&mdash;Yes&mdash;now he is beyond the porch, bar|ring
the outer gate! Alonzo!&mdash;Alonzo!&mdash;my
friend! Ha!&mdash;in gentle &s;leep!&mdash;Alonzo&mdash;ri&s;e!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>How!&mdash;Is my hour elaps'd?&mdash;Well, <STAGE>(re|turning
from the rece&s;s,)</STAGE> I am ready.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alonzo,&mdash;know me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>What voice is that?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis Rolla's.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>Rolla!&mdash;my friend!&mdash;<STAGE>(Embraces him.)</STAGE> Hea|vens!
how coud'&s;t thou pa&s;s the guard? Did this
habit&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="53" REF="60">
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>There is not a moment to be lo&s;t in words;
&mdash;this di&s;gui&s;e I tore from the dead body of a
Friar, as I pa&s;s'd our field of battle&mdash;it has gain'd
me entrance to thy dungeon&mdash;now take it thou,
and fly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>And Rolla&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Will remain here in thy place.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>And die for me!&mdash;No!&mdash;Rather eternal
tortures rack me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall not die, Alonzo.&mdash;It is thy life Pi|zarro
&s;eeks, not Rolla's&mdash;and from my pri&s;on &s;oon
will thy arm deliver me;&mdash;or, &s;hould it be other|wi&s;e&mdash;I
am as a blighted plantain &s;tanding alone
amid the &s;andy de&s;ert&mdash;Nothing &s;eeks or lives be|neath
my &s;helter&mdash;Thou art a hu&s;band, and a fa|ther&mdash;The
being of a lovely wife and helple&s;s in|fant
hang upon thy life&mdash;Go!&mdash;Go!&mdash;Alonzo!&mdash;Go&mdash;to
&s;ave&mdash;not thy&s;elf&mdash;but Cora, and thy
child!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>Urge me not thus, my friend&mdash;I had pre|par'd
to die in peace.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>To die in peace!&mdash;devoting her you've
&s;worn to live for,&mdash;to madne&s;s, mi&s;ery, and death!
&mdash;For, be a&s;&s;ured&mdash;the &s;tate I left her in forbids all
hope, but from thy quick return.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! God!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>If thou art yet irre&s;olute, Alonzo&mdash;now
heed me well.&mdash;I think thou ha&s;t not known that
Rolla ever pledg'd his word, and &s;hrunk from its
fulfilment.&mdash;And, by the heart of truth I &s;wear,
if thou art proudly ob&s;tinate to deny thy friend
the tran&s;port of pre&s;erving Cora's life, in thee,&mdash;no
power that &s;ways the will of man &s;hall &s;tir me
hence&mdash;and thou'lt but have the de&s;perate tri|umph,
of &s;eeing Rolla peri&s;h by thy &s;ide,&mdash;with
<PB N="54" REF="61">
the a&s;&s;ur'd conviction, that Cora, and thy child,
are lo&s;t for ever.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! Rolla!&mdash;you di&s;tract me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>A moment's further pau&s;e, and all is lo&s;t&mdash;The
dawn approaches&mdash;Fear not for me&mdash;I will
treat with Pizarro as for &s;urrender and &s;ubmi&s;&s;ion;
&mdash;I &s;hall gain time, doubt not&mdash;while thou, with
a cho&s;en band, pa&s;&s;ing the &s;ecret way, may'&s;t at
night return&mdash;relea&s;e thy friend, and bear him
back in triumph&mdash;Yes&mdash;ha&s;ten&mdash;dear Alonzo!&mdash;Even
now I hear the frantic Cora call thee!&mdash;Ha&s;te!&mdash;Ha&s;te!&mdash;Ha&s;te!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>Rolla, I fear your friend&s;hip drives me from
honour, and from right.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Did Rolla ever coun&s;el di&s;honour to his
friend?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! my pre&s;erver!&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(Embracing him.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>I feel thy warm tears dropping on my
cheek&mdash;Go!&mdash;I am rewarded&mdash;(<HI>Throws the Friar's
garment over Alonzo.</HI>)&mdash;There! conceal thy face;
and that they may not clank, hold fa&s;t thy chains&mdash;Now&mdash;God
be with thee!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>At night we meet again.&mdash;Then,&mdash;&s;o aid
me Heaven! I return to &s;ave&mdash;or&mdash;peri&s;h with
thee!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(alone.)</STAGE>
<P>He has pa&s;s'd the outer porch&mdash;He
is &s;afe!&mdash;He will &s;oon embrace his wife and child!
&mdash;Now, Cora, did'&s;t thou not wrong me? This
is the fir&s;t time throughout my life I ever deceived
men&mdash;Forgive
me, God of truth! if I am wrong&mdash;A$onzo
flatters him&s;elf that we &s;hall meet again&mdash;Yes&mdash;There!
<STAGE>(lifting his hands to heaven)</STAGE> a&s;&s;uredly,
we &s;hall meet again:&mdash;there po&s;&s;e&s;s in peace, the
joys of everla&s;ting love, and friend&s;hip&mdash;on earth,
imperfect, and embitter'd&mdash;I will retire, le&s;t the
guard return before Alonzo may have pa&s;s'd their
lines.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Retires into the Rece&s;s.</STAGE>
<PB N="55" REF="62">
<STAGE>Enter <HI>ELVIRA.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;not Pizarro's brutal taunts&mdash;not the
glowing admiration which I feel for this noble
youth, &s;hall rai&s;e an intere&s;t in this hara&s;s'd bo&s;om
which honour would not &s;anction. If he reject
the vengeance my heart has &s;worn again&s;t the ty|rant,
who's death alone can &s;ave this land&mdash;yet,
&s;hall the delight be mine to re&s;tore him to his Co|ra's
arms, to his dear child, and to the unoffend|ing
people, whom his virtues guide, and valour
guards.&mdash;Alonzo, come forth!</P>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>ROLLA.</HI></STAGE>
<P>Ha!&mdash;who art thou?&mdash;Where is Alonzo?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alonzo's fled.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fled!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes&mdash;and he mu&s;t not be pur&s;ued&mdash;Par|don
this roughne&s;s, <STAGE>(&s;eizing her hand)</STAGE>&mdash;but a mo|ment's
precious to Alonzo's flight.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>What if I call the guard?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do &s;o&mdash;Alonzo &s;till gains time.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>What if thus I free my&s;elf?</P>
<STAGE>(Shews a
dagger.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Strike it to my heart&mdash;Still, with the con|vul&s;ive
gra&s;p of death, I'll hold thee fa&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Relea&s;e me&mdash;I give my faith, I neither will
alarm the guard, nor cau&s;e pur&s;uit.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>At once, I tru&s;t thy word&mdash;A feeling bold|ne&s;s
in tho&s;e eyes a&s;&s;ures me that thy &s;oul is noble.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>What is thy name? Speak freely&mdash;By my
order the guard is remov'd beyond the outer porch.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>My name is Rolla.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="56" REF="63">
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>The Peruvian Leader?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>I was &s;o ye&s;terday&mdash;to-day, the Spaniard's
captive.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>And friend&s;hip for Alonzo, moved thee to
this act?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alonzo is my friend&mdash;I am prepared to die
for him. Yet is the cau&s;e a motive &s;tronger far
than friend&s;hip.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>One only pa&s;&s;ion el&s;e could urge &s;uch ge|nerous
ra&s;hne&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>And that is&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Love?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>True!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Gallant!&mdash;ingenious Rolla!&mdash;Know that
my purpo&s;e here was thine; and were I to &s;ave
thy friend&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>How!&mdash;a woman ble&s;s'd with gentlene&s;s
and courage, and yet not Cora!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Does Rolla think &s;o meanly of all female
hearts?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not &s;o&mdash;you are wor&s;e and better than we
are!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>To &s;ave thee, Rolla, from the tyrant's
vengeance&mdash;re&s;tore thee to thy native land&mdash;and
thy native land to peace&mdash;would'&s;t thou not rank
Elvira with the good?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>To judge the action, I mu&s;t know the
means.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Take this dagger.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>How to be u&s;ed?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will conduct thee to the tent where fell
Pizarro &s;leeps&mdash;The &s;courge of innocence&mdash;the
terror of thy race&mdash;the fiend, that de&s;olates thy
afflicted country.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Have you not been injur'd by Pizarro?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="57" REF="64">
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Deeply as &s;corn and in&s;ult can infu&s;e their
deadly venom.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>And you a&s;k that I &s;hall murder him in his
&s;leep!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Would not he have murder'd Alonzo in
his chains? He that &s;leeps, and he that's bound,
are equally defencele&s;s. Hear me, Rolla&mdash;&s;o may
I pro&s;per in this perilous act as &s;earching my full
heart, I have put by all rancorous motive of pri|vate
vengeance there, and feel that I advance to
my dread purpo&s;e in the cau&s;e of human nature,
and at the call of &s;acred ju&s;tice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>The God of ju&s;tice &s;anctifies no evil as
a &s;tep towards good. Great actions cannot be
achieved by wicked means.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, Peruvian! &s;ince thou do'&s;t feel &s;o
coldly for thy country's wrongs, this hand, tho'
it revolt my &s;oul, &s;hall &s;trike the blow.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then is thy de&s;truction certain, and for
Peru thou peri&s;he&s;t!&mdash;Give me the dagger!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now follow me;&mdash;but fir&s;t&mdash;and dreadful
is the hard nece&s;&s;ity&mdash;you mu&s;t &s;trike down the
guard.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>The &s;oldier who was on duty here?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, him&mdash;el&s;e, &s;eeing thee, the alarm
will be in&s;tant.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I mu&s;t &s;tab that &s;oldier as I pa&s;s?&mdash;Take
back thy dagger.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Rolla!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>That &s;oldier, mark me, is a man.&mdash;All
are not men that bear the human form. He re|fus'd
my prayers&mdash;refus'd my gold&mdash;denying to
admit me&mdash;till his own feelings brib'd him.&mdash;For
my nation's &s;afety, I would not harm that man!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then he mu&s;t be with us&mdash;I will an&s;wer for
his &s;afety.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="58" REF="65">
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be that plainly under&s;tood between us:&mdash;for,
whate'er betide our enterprize, I will not ri&s;k
a hair of that man's head, to &s;ave my heart&s;trings
from con&s;uming fire.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE III.</HEAD>
<STAGE>The in&s;ide of Pizarro's Tent.&mdash;Pizarro on a Couch,
in di&s;turbed &s;leep.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(in his &s;leep.)</STAGE>
<P>No mercy, traitor.&mdash;Now at
his heart!&mdash;Stand off there, you&mdash;Let me &s;ee him
bleed!&mdash;Ha! ha! ha!&mdash;Let me hear that groan
again.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>ROLLA</HI> and <HI>EL VIRA.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tere!&mdash;Now, lo&s;e not a moment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>You mu&s;t leave me now.&mdash;This &s;cene of
blood fits not a woman's pre&s;ence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>But a moment's pau&s;e may&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Go!&mdash;Retire to your own tent&mdash;and return
not here&mdash;I will come to you.&mdash;Be thou not known
in this bu&s;ine&s;s, I implore you!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will withdraw the guard that waits.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit Elvira.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now have I in my power the accurs'd de|&s;troyer
of my country's peace: yet tranquilly he
re&s;ts.&mdash;God!&mdash;can this man &s;leep?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(in his &s;leep.)</STAGE>
<P>Away! away!&mdash;Hideous
fiends!&mdash;Tear not my bo&s;om thus!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>No: I was in error&mdash;the balm of &s;weet
repo&s;e he never more can know.&mdash;Look here, am|bition's
fools!&mdash;Ye, by who&s;e inhuman pride, the
bleeding &s;acrifice of nations is held as nothing&mdash;behold
the re&s;t of the guilty!&mdash;He is at my mercy
&mdash;and one blow!&mdash;No!&mdash;my heart and hand re|fu&s;e
the act: Rolla cannot be an a&s;&s;a&s;&s;in!&mdash;Yet
<PB N="59" REF="66">
Elvira mu&s;t be &s;aved! <STAGE>(Approaches the Couch.)</STAGE> Piz|zaro!
awake!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Starts up.)</STAGE>
<P>Who?&mdash;Guard!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Speak not&mdash;another word is thy death&mdash;Call
not for aid&mdash;this arm will be &s;wifter than thy
guard.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who art thou? and what is thy will?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am thine enemy! Peruvian Rolla!&mdash;Thy
death is not my will, or I could have &s;lain thee
&s;leeping.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Speak, what el&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now thou art at my mercy&mdash;an&s;wer me I
Did a Peruvian ever yet wrong or injure thee, or
any of thy nation? Did&s;t thou, or any of thy
nation, ever yet &s;hew mercy to a Peruvian in your
power? Now &s;halt thou feel&mdash;and if thou ha&s;t a
heart, thou'lt feel it keenly!&mdash;a Peruvian's venge|ance!
<STAGE>(Drops the dagger at his feet)</STAGE> There!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is it po&s;&s;ible!</P>
<STAGE>(Walks a&s;ide confounded.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Can Pizarro be &s;urprized at this? I thought
Forgivene&s;s of Injuries had been the Chri&s;tian's
precept&mdash;Thou &s;ee&s;t, at lea&s;t, it is the Peruvian's
practice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Rolla&mdash;thou ha&s;t indeed &s;urpris'd&mdash;&s;ubdued
me.</P>
<STAGE>(Walks again a&s;ide as in irre&s;olute thought.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE>Re-enter <HI>ELVIRA,</HI> (not &s;eeing Pizarro.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is it done? Is he dead? <STAGE>(Sees Pizarro)</STAGE>
How!&mdash;&s;till living! Then I am lo&s;t! And for
you, wretched Peruvians! mercy is no more!&mdash;Oh!
Rolla! treacherous or cowardly?&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>How can it be, that&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Away! Elvira &s;peaks &s;he knows not what!
Leave me, <STAGE>(to Elvira)</STAGE> I conjure you, with Pizarro.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>How!&mdash;Rolla, do'&s;t thou think I &s;hall re|tract
<PB N="60" REF="67">
&mdash;or that I meanly will deny, that in thy hand
I plac'd a poignard to be plung'd into that tyrant's
heart? No:&mdash;my &s;ole regret is, that I tru&s;ted to
thy weakne&s;s, and did not &s;trike the blow my&s;elf.
Too &s;oon thou'lt learn that mercy to that man is
direct cruelty to all thy race!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Guard! quick! a guard to &s;eize this fran|tic
woman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, a guard! I call them too! And &s;oon
I know they'll lead me to my death. But think
not, Pizarro, the fury of thy fla&s;hing eyes &s;hall
awe me for a moment!&mdash;Nor think that woman's
anger, or the feelings of an injured heart, prompted
me to this de&s;ign&mdash;No! Had I been only influ|enced
&s;o&mdash;thus failing, &s;hame and remor&s;e
would weigh me down. But though defeated and
de&s;troyed, as now I am, &s;uch is the greatne&s;s and
the cau&s;e that urged me, I &s;hall peri&s;h, glorying
in the attempt, and my la&s;t breath of life &s;hall
&s;peak the proud avowal of my purpo&s;e&mdash;to have
re&s;cued millions of innocents from the blood|thir&s;ty
tyranny of ONE&mdash;by ridding the in&s;ulted
world of THEE.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Had the act been noble as the motive&mdash;Rolla
would not have &s;hrunk from its perform|ance.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter Guards.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Seize this di&s;covered fiend, who &s;ought to
kill your Leader.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Touch me not, at the peril of your &s;ouls;
&mdash;I am your pri&s;oner, and will follow you. But
thou, their triumphant Leader, &s;hall hear me. Yet,
fir&s;t&mdash;for thee, Rolla, accept my forgivene&s;s: even
had I been the victim of thy noblene&s;s of heart, I
&s;hould have admired thee for it&mdash;But 'twas my&s;elf
<PB N="61" REF="68">
provok'd my doom&mdash;Thou would'&s;t have &s;hielded
me.&mdash;Let not thy contempt follow me to the
grave. Did&s;t thou but know the &s;pell-like arts, by
which this hypocrite fir&s;t undermined the virtue of
a guilele&s;s heart! how, even in the pious &s;anctuary
wherein I dwelt, by corruption and by fraud, he
practis'd upon tho&s;e in whom I mo&s;t confided&mdash;'till
my di&s;tempered fancy'led me, &s;tep by &s;tep, into the
aby&s;s of guilt&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why am I not obeyed?&mdash;Tear her hence!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis pa&s;t&mdash;but did&s;t thou know my &s;tory,
Rolla, thou would'&s;t pity me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>From my &s;oul I do pity thee!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Villains! drag her to the dungeon!&mdash;prepare
the torture in&s;tantly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Soldiers&mdash;but a moment more&mdash;'Tis to
applaud your General&mdash;It is to tell the a&s;toni&s;hed
world, that, for once, Pizarro's &s;entence is an
act of ju&s;tice. Yes, rack me with the &s;harpe&s;t
tortures that ever agoniz'd the human frame; it
will be ju&s;tice. Yes&mdash;bid the minions of thy
fury&mdash;wrench forth the &s;inews of tho&s;e arms that
have care&s;s'd, and&mdash;even have defended thee!
Bid them pour burning metal into the bleeding
ca&s;es of tho&s;e eyes, that &s;o oft&mdash;oh God!&mdash;have
hung with love and homage on thy looks&mdash;then
approach me, bound on the abhorred wheel&mdash;there
glut thy &s;avage eyes with the convul&s;ive
&s;pa&s;ms of what di&s;honoured bo&s;om, which was
once thy pillow!&mdash;Yet, will I bear it all; for it
will be ju&s;tice, all! And when thou &s;halt bid
them tear me to my death, hoping that thy un|&s;hrinking
ears may at la&s;t be fea&s;ted with the
mu&s;ic of my cries, I will not utter one &s;hriek or
groan&mdash;but. to the la&s;t ga&s;p, my body's patience
<PB N="62" REF="69">
&s;hall deride thy vengeance, as my &s;oul defies thy
power.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Endeavouring to conceal his agitation.)</STAGE>
<P>Hear'&s;t thou the wretch who&s;e hands were even
now prepared for murder?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes! And if her accu&s;ation's fal&s;e, thou
wilt not &s;hrink from hearing her$ if true, thy bar|barity
cannot make <HI>her</HI> &s;uffer the pangs thy con|&s;cience
will inflict on <HI>thee.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>And now, farewell, world!&mdash;Rolla, fare|well!
&mdash;Farewell! thou condemued of Heaven!
<STAGE>(to Pizarro;)</STAGE>&mdash;for repentance and remor&s;e, I
know, will never touch thy heart. We &s;hall meet
again. Ha! be it thy horror here, to know that
we &s;hall meet hereafter! And when thy parting
hour approaches&mdash;hark to the knell, who&s;e dread|ful
beat will &s;trike to thy de&s;pairing &s;oul. Then,
will vibrate on thy ear the cur&s;es of the cloi&s;ter'd
&s;aint from whom you &s;tole me. Then, the la&s;t
&s;hrieks which bur&s;t from my mother's breaking
heart, as &s;he died, appealing to her God again&s;t the
&s;educer of her child! Then the blood-&s;tifled groan
of my murdered brother&mdash;murdered by thee, fell
mon&s;ter!&mdash;&s;eeking atonement for his &s;i&s;ter's ruin'd
honour. I hear them now! To me the recollec|tion's
madne&s;s!&mdash;At &s;uch an hour,&mdash;what will it be
to thee?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>A moment's more delay, and at the peril of
your lives&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have &s;poken&mdash;and the la&s;t mortal frailty
of my heart is pa&s;t&mdash;And now, with an undaunted
&s;pirit, and un&s;haken firmne&s;s, I go to meet my
de&s;tiny. That I could not <HI>live</HI> nobly, has been
PIZARRO'S ACT. That I will <HI>die</HI> nobly, &s;hall be
my own.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit, guarded.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Rolla, I would not thou, a warrior,
<PB N="63" REF="70">
valiant and renowned, &s;hould'&s;t credit the vile
tales of this frantic woman. The cau&s;e of all this
fury&mdash;O! a wanton pa&s;&s;ion for the rebel youth
Alonzo, now my pri&s;oner.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alonzo is not now thy pri&s;oner.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>How!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>I came to re&s;cue him&mdash;to deceive his
guard&mdash;I have &s;ucceeded;&mdash;<HI>I</HI> remain thy pri|&s;oner.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alonzo fled?&mdash;Is then the vengeance dear|e&s;t
to my heart never to be gratified?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Di&s;mi&s;s &s;uch pa&s;&s;ions from thy heart; then
thou'lt con&s;ult its peace.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can face all enemies that dare confront me
&mdash;I cannot war again&s;t my nature.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, Pizarro, a&s;k not to be deemed a
hero&mdash;To triumph o'er our&s;elves is the only con|que&s;t,
where fortune makes no claim. In battle,
chance may &s;natch the laurel from thee, or chance
may place it on thy brow&mdash;but in a conte&s;t with
your&s;elf, be re&s;olute, and the virtuous impul&s;e mu&s;t
be the victor.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Peruvian! thou &s;halt not find me to <HI>thee</HI> un|grateful,
or ungenerous&mdash;Return to your country|men
&mdash;You are at liberty.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thou do'&s;t act in this, as honour, and as du|ty,
bid thee.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>I cannot but admire, thee, Rolla, I wou'd
we might be friends.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Farewell. Pity Elvira! Become the
friend of virtue&mdash;and thou wilt be mine</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit&punc;</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ambition! tell me what is the phantom
I have followed? where is the one delight which
it has made my own? My fame is the mark of
envy&mdash;my love the dupe of treachery&mdash;my glory
<PB N="64" REF="71">
eclips'd by the boy I taught&mdash;my revenge de|feated
and rebuked by the rude honour of a &s;avage
$oe&mdash;before who&s;e native dignity of &s;oul I have &s;unk
confounded and &s;ubdued! I would I cou'd retrace
my &s;teps&mdash;I cannot&mdash;Would I could evade my own
reflections!&mdash;No!&mdash;thought and memory are my
Hell.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<TRAILER>END OF THE FOURTH ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="5" TYPE="act">
<PB N="65" REF="72">
<HEAD>ACT V.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE I.</HEAD>
<STAGE>A thick Fore&s;t&mdash;In the back ground, a Hut almo&s;t
covered by Boughs of Trees&mdash;A dreadful Storm,
with Thunder and Lightning.&mdash;<HI>CORA</HI> has covered
her Child on a bed of Leaves and Mo&s;s&mdash;her whole
appearance is wild and di&s;tracted.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>O NATURE! thou ha&s;t not the &s;trength
of love. My anxious &s;pirit is untired in its
march; my wearied &s;hivering frame &s;inks under
it. And, for thee, my boy&mdash;when faint beneath
thy lovely burden, could I refu&s;e to give thy
&s;lumbers that poor bed of re&s;t! O my child!
were I a&s;&s;ured thy father breathes no more,
how qui$kly would I lay me down by thy dear
&s;ide&mdash;but down&mdash;down for ever. (<HI>Thunder and
Lightning.</HI>) I a&s;k thee not, unpi$ying &s;torm! to
abate thy rage, in mercy to poor Cora's mi&s;ery;
nor while thy thunders &s;pares his &s;lumbers will I
di&s;turb my &s;leeping cherub. Though Heaven knows
I wi&s;h to hear the voice of life, and feel that life
is near me. But I will endure all while what I
have of rea&s;on holds.</P>
</SP>
<DIV4 TYPE="song">
<HEAD>SONG.</HEAD>
<L>Yes, yes, be mercile&s;s, thou Tempe&s;t dire;</L>
<L>Unaw'd, un&s;heltered, I thy fury brave,</L>
<L>I'll bare my bo&s;om to thy forked fire,</L>
<L>Let it but guide me to ALONZO'S grave!</L>
<L>O'er his pale cor&s;e then while thy lightnings glare,</L>
<L>I'll pre&s;s thy clay-cold lips, and peri&s;h there:</L>
<L>But thou wilt wake again, my boy,</L>
<L>Again thou'lt ri&s;e to life and joy,</L>
<L>Thy father never!</L>
<L>Thy laghing eyes will meet the light,</L>
<L>Uncon&s;cious that eternal night</L>
<L>Veils his for ever.</L>
<L><PB N="66" REF="73">
On yon green bed of mo&s;s there lies my child,</L>
<L>Oh! &s;afer lies from the&s;e chill'd arms apart;</L>
<L>He &s;leeps, &s;weet lamb! nor heeds the tempe&s;t wild,</L>
<L>Oh! &s;weeter &s;leeps, than near this breaking heart.</L>
<L>Alas! my babe, if thou would'&s;t peaceful re&s;t,</L>
<L>Thy cradle mu&s;t not be thy mother's brea&s;t.</L>
<L>Yet, thou wilt wake again, my boy,</L>
<L>Again thou'lt ri&s;e to life and joy,</L>
<L>Thy father never!&mdash;</L>
<L>Thy laughing eyes will meet the light,</L>
<L>Uncon&s;cious that eternal night</L>
<L>Veils his for ever.</L>
<STAGE>(Thunder and Lightning.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Still, &s;till, implacable! unfeeling elements!
yet &s;till do&s;t thou &s;leep, my &s;miling innocent! O,
death! when wilt thou grant to this babe's mother
&s;uch repo&s;e? Sure I may &s;hield thee better from
the &s;torm; my veil may&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>While &s;he is wrapping her mantle and her
veil over him, <HI>Alonzo's</HI> voice is heard as
a great&punc; di&s;tance.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>Cora!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hah!!!</P>
<STAGE>(ri&s;es)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(again)</STAGE>
<P>Cora!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora,</SPEAKER>
<P>O, my heart! Sweet Heaven deceive me
not! Is it not Alonzo's voice?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(nearer)</STAGE>
<P>Cora!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is&mdash;it is Alonzo!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(nearer &s;till)</STAGE>
<P>Cora! my beloved!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alonzo! Here! here! Alonzo!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Runs out.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Enter two Spani&s;h Soldiers.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1 &s;t Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>I tell you we are near our out-po&s;ts, and
the word we heard ju&s;t now was the counter&s;ign.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="67" REF="74">
<SPEAKER>2d Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, in our e&s;cape from the enemy, to
have di&s;cover'd their &s;ecret pa&s;&s;age thro' the rocks,
will prove a lucky chance to us&mdash;Pizarro will re|ward
us.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1 &s;t Sol</SPEAKER>
<P>This way&mdash;The &s;un, though clouded,
is on our left. <STAGE>(Perceives the child.)</STAGE> What have we
here?&mdash;A child!&mdash;as I'm a &s;oldier.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2d Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis a &s;weet little babe. Now would it
be a great charity to take this infant from its pagan
mother's power.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1 &s;t Sol.</SPEAKER>
<P>It would &s;o&mdash;I have one at home &s;hall
play with it.&mdash;Come along.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Takes the child. Exeunt.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Re-enter <HI>CORA</HI> with <HI>ALONZO.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(&s;peaking without).</STAGE>
<P>This way, dear Alon|zo.
Now am I right&mdash;there&mdash;there&mdash;under that
tree. Was it po&s;&s;ible the in&s;tinct of a mother's
heart could mi&s;take the &s;pot! Now will you look
at him as he &s;leeps, or &s;hall I bring him waking
with his full blue laughing eyes to welcome you at
once&mdash;Yes&mdash;yes.&mdash;Stand thou there&mdash;I'll &s;natch
him from his ro&s;y &s;lumber, blu&s;hing like the per|&s;um'd
morn</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>She runs up to the &s;pot, and, finding only
the mantle and veil, which &s;he tears from
the ground, and the child gone, <STAGE>(&s;hrieks)</STAGE>
and &s;tands in &s;peechle&s;s agony.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(running to her).</STAGE>
<P>Cora!&mdash;my heart's be|loved!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>He is gone!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eternal God!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>He is gone!&mdash;my child! my child!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>Where did you leave him?</P>
<P>Cora <STAGE>(da&s;hing her&s;elf on the &s;pot).</STAGE> <HI>Here!</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be calm, beloved Cora&mdash;he has wak'd, and
<PB N="68" REF="75">
crept to a little di&s;tance&mdash;we &s;hall find him&mdash;Are
you a&s;&s;ured this was the &s;pot you left him in?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Did not the&s;e hands make that bed, and
&s;helter for him? and is not this the veil that co|vered
him?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here is a hut yet unob&s;erved.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! yes, yes! there lives the &s;avage that
has rob'd me of my child&mdash;<STAGE>(Beats at the door, ex|claiming)</STAGE>
Give me back my child&mdash;re&s;tore to me
my boy!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>LAS CASAS</HI> from the Hut.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Las. C.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who calls me from my wretched &s;oli|tude?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Give me back my child! <STAGE>(Goes into the
hut, and calls)</STAGE> Fernando!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>Almighty powers! do my eyes deceive me!
Las Ca&s;as!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Las C.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alonzo,&mdash;my belov'd young friend!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>My rever'd in&s;tructor.</P>
<STAGE>(Embracing&punc;)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Returned).</STAGE>
<P>Will you embrace this man
before he re&s;tores my boy?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alas, my friend&mdash;in what a moment of mi|&s;ery
do we meet!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yet his look is goodne&s;s and humanity.&mdash;Good
old man, have compa&s;&s;ion on a wretched
mother&mdash;and I will be your &s;ervant while I live.&mdash;But
do not, for pity's &s;ake&mdash;do not &s;ay, you have
him not&mdash;do not &s;ay, you have not &s;een him.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Runs into the Wood.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Las C.</SPEAKER>
<P>What can this mean?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>She is my wife, ju&s;t re&s;cued from the Spa|niards'
pri&s;on.&mdash;I learn'd &s;he had fled to this wild
fore&s;t&mdash;Hearing my voice, &s;he left the child, and
flew to meet me&mdash;he was left &s;leeping under yon|der
tree.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="69" REF="76">
<SPEAKER>Las C.</SPEAKER>
<P>How! did you <HI>leave</HI> him?&mdash;<HI>Cora re|turns).</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, you are right!&mdash;right!&mdash;unnatural
mother, that I was&mdash;I left my child&mdash;I for&s;ook
my innocent&mdash;but I will fly to the earth's brink,
but I will find him.</P>
<STAGE>(Runs out&punc;)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Al.</SPEAKER>
<P>Forgive me, Las Ca&s;as, I mu&s;t follow her?
for at night, I mu&s;t attempt brave Rolla's re&s;cue.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Las C.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will not leave thee, Alonzo&mdash;you mu&s;t
try to lead her to the right&mdash;that way lies your
camp&mdash;Wait not my infirm &s;teps,&mdash;I follow thee,
my friend.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE>
</DIV4>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE II.</HEAD>
<STAGE>The Out-Po&s;t of the Spani&s;h Camp.&mdash;The back ground
wild and rocky, with a Torrent falling down the
Precipice, over which a Bridge is formed. A
fell'd Tree.</STAGE>
<STAGE>[Trumpets &s;ound without.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Almagro</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(without).</STAGE>
<P>Bear him along&mdash;his &s;tory
mu&s;t be fal&s;e.</P>
<STAGE>(Entering).</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>ROLLA</HI> (in chains) brought in by Soldiers.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fal&s;e!&mdash;Rolla, utter fal&s;ehood '&mdash;I would
I had thee in a de&s;ert with thy troop around thee;
&mdash;and I, but with my &s;word in this un&s;hackled
hand!&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(Trumpets without.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alm.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is it to be credited that Rolla, the renown'd
Peruvian hero&mdash;&s;hou'd be detected like a &s;py,
&s;kulking through our camp?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Skulking!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alm.</SPEAKER>
<P>But an&s;wer to the General&mdash;he is here.</P>
</SP>
<PB N="70" REF="77">
<STAGE>Enter <HI>PIZARRO.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>What do I &s;ee! Rolla!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>O! to thy &s;urpri&s;e, no doubt.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>And bound too!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>So fa&s;t, thou need'&s;t not fear approaching
me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alm.</SPEAKER>
<P>The guards &s;urpris'd him, pa&s;&s;ing our out|po&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Relea&s;e him in&s;tantly.&mdash;Believe me, I re|gret
this in&s;ult.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>You feel then as you ought.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nor can I brook to &s;ee a warrior of Rolla's
&s;ame di&s;arm'd&mdash;accept this, tho' it has been thy
enemy's. <STAGE>(Gives a &s;word.)</STAGE> The Spaniards know
the courte&s;y that's due to valour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>And the Peruvian, how to forget offence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>May not Rolla and Pizarro cea&s;e to be
fo?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>When the &s;ea divides us; yes!&mdash;May I
now depart?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Freely.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;hall I not again be intercepted?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>No!&mdash;let the word be given that Rolla
pa&s;&s;es freely.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>DAVILLA</HI> and Soldiers, with the Child.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dav.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here are two &s;oldiers, captived ye&s;terday,
who have e&s;cap'd from the Peruvian hold,&mdash;and
by the &s;ecret way we have &s;o long endeavoured to
di&s;cover.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Silence, imprudent! See&s;t thou not&mdash;?</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Pointing to</HI> Rolla.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dav.</SPEAKER>
<P>In their way, they found a Peruvian child,
who &s;eems&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="71" REF="78">
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>What is the imp to me?&mdash;Bid them to&s;s it
into the &s;ea.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Gracious heaven! it is Alonzo's child!&mdash;give
it to me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! Alonzo's child! Welcome, thou
pretty ho&s;tage. Now Alonzo is again my pri|&s;oner!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thou wilt not keep the infant from its mo|ther?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Will I not! What, when I &s;hall meet
Alonzo in the heat of the victorious fight, think'&s;t
thou I &s;hall not have a check upon the valour of
his heart, when he is reminded that a word of
mine is this child's death?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do not under&s;tand you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>My vengeance has a long arrear of hate to
&s;ettle with Alonzo! and this pledge may help to
&s;ettle the account.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Man! Man! Art thou a man? Could'&s;t
thou hurt that innoc$nt? By Heaven! its &s;miling
in thy face.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tell me, does it re&s;emble Cora?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pizarro! thou ha&s;t &s;et my heart on fire
&mdash;If thou do'&s;t harm that child, think not his blood
will &s;ink into the barren &s;and; No! faithful to the
eager hope that now trembles in this indignant
heart, 'twill ri&s;e to the common God of nature
and humanity, and cry aloud for vengeance on its
accur&s;ed de&s;troyer's <HI>head.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be that peril mine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(throwing him&s;elf at his feet).</STAGE>
<P>Behold me at
thy feet&mdash;Me, Rolla!&mdash;Me, the pre&s;erver of thy
life&mdash;Me, that have never yet bent or bow'd be|fore
created man!&mdash;In humble agony I &s;ue to you
&mdash;pro&s;trate I implore you&mdash;but &s;pare that child,
and I will be your &s;lave.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="72" REF="79">
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Rolla! &s;till art thou free to go&mdash;this boy
remains with me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then was this &s;word Heaven's gift, not
thine! <HI>Seizes the Child</HI>)&mdash;Who moves one &s;tep to
follow me, dies upon the &s;pot.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit, with the Child.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pur&s;ue him in&s;tantly&mdash;but &s;pare his life.
<HI>[Exeunt Almagro and &s;oldiers.]</HI> With what fury
he defends him&s;elf!&mdash;Ha!&mdash;he fells them to the
ground&mdash;and now&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>ALMAGRO.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alm.</SPEAKER>
<P>Three of your brave &s;oldiers are already
victims to your command to &s;pare this madman's
life; and if he once gains the thicket&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Spare him no longer. <STAGE><HI>[Exit</HI> Almagro.]</STAGE>
Their guns mu&s;t reach him&mdash;he'll yet e&s;cape&mdash;hollow
to tho&s;e hor&s;e&mdash;the Peruvian &s;ees them
&mdash;and now he turns among the rocks&mdash;then is his
retreat cut off.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>[Rolla</SPEAKER>
<P>cro&s;&s;es a wooden bridge over the cataract,
pur&s;ued by the &s;oldiers&mdash;they fire at him&mdash;a &s;hot
&s;trikes him&mdash;Pizarro exclaims&mdash;</P>
<P>Piz. <HI>Now! quick! quick! &s;eize the child!&mdash;</HI>
[Rolla tears from the rock the tree which &s;upports the
bridge, and retreats by the back ground, bearing
off the child.]</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Re-enter <HI>ALMAGRO.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alm.</SPEAKER>
<P>By Hell! he has e&s;caped!&mdash;and with the
child unhurt.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dav.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;he bears his death with him&mdash;Be|lieve
me, I &s;aw him &s;truck upon the &s;ide.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>But the child is &s;av'd&mdash;Alonzo's child!
Oh! the furies of di&s;appointed vengeance!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="73" REF="80">
<SPEAKER>Alm.</SPEAKER>
<P>Away with the revenge of words&mdash;let us
to deeds&mdash;Forget not we have acquired the
knowledge of the &s;ecret pa&s;s, which thro' the
rocky cavern's gloom brings you at once to the
&s;trong hold, where are lodged their women and
their trea&s;ures.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Right, Almagro! Swift as thy thought
draw forth a daring and a cho&s;en band&mdash;I will
not wait for numbers.&mdash;Stay, Almagro! Val|verde
is informed Elvira dies to-day?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Val.</SPEAKER>
<P>He is&mdash;and one reque&s;t alone &s;he&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll hear of none.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Val.</SPEAKER>
<P>The boon is &s;mall&mdash;'tis but for the no|viciate
habit which you fir&s;t beheld her in&mdash;&s;he
wi&s;hes not to &s;uffer in the gaudy trappings, which
remind her of her &s;hame.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, do as thou wilt&mdash;but tell Valverde,
that at our return, as his life &s;hall an&s;wer it, to
let me hear that &s;he is dead.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exeunt &s;everally.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE III.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Ataliba's Tent.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ATALIBA, <HI>followed by</HI> CORA <HI>and</HI> ALONZO.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! avoid me not, Ataliba! To whom,
but to her King, is the wretched mother to addre&s;s
her griefs?&mdash;The Gods refu&s;e to hear my prayers!
Did not my Alonzo fight for <HI>you?</HI>&mdash;and will not
my &s;weet boy, if thou'lt but re&s;tore him to me,
one day fight thy battles too?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! my &s;uffering love&mdash;my poor heart-broken
Cora!&mdash;you but wound our Sovereign's
feeling &s;oul, and not relieve thy own.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is he our &s;overeign, and has he not the
power to give me back my child?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="74" REF="81">
<SPEAKER>Ata.</SPEAKER>
<P>When I reward de&s;ert, or can relieve my
people, I feel what is the real glory of a King&mdash;when
I hear them &s;uffer, and cannot aid them,
I mourn the impotence of all mortal power.</P>
<STAGE>(Voices behind)</STAGE>
<P>Rolla! Rolla! Rolla!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>ROLLA,</HI> bleeding with the child, follow'd by
Peruvian &s;oldiers.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thy child!</P>
<STAGE>(Gives the child into Cora's
arms, and falls.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cora.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh God!&mdash;there's blood upon him!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis my blood, Cora!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Rolla, thou die&s;t!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rol.</SPEAKER>
<P>For thee, and Cora.&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(Dies.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>ORANO.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Orano.</SPEAKER>
<P>Treachery has revealed our a&s;ylum in the
rocks. Even now the foe a&s;&s;ails the peaceful band
retired for protection there.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lo&s;e not a moment!&mdash;Swords be quick. $</P>
<P>&mdash;Your wives and children cry to you&mdash;Bear our
lov'd hero's body in the van&mdash;'Twill rai&s;e the
fury of our men to madne&s;s.&mdash;Now, fell Pizarro!
the death of one of us is near!&mdash;Away! Be the
word of a&s;&s;ault, Revenge and Rolla!&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>[<HI>Exeunt.</HI> (CHARGE.)</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE IV.</HEAD>
<STAGE>A romantic part of the Rece&s;s among the Rocks&mdash;(<HI>Alarms</HI>)
Women are &s;een &s;tying, pur&s;ued by the
Spani&s;h Soldiers.&mdash;The Peruvian &s;oldiers drive the
Spani$rds back from the Field.&mdash;The Fight is con|tinued
on the Heights.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> PIZARRO, ALMAGRO, VALVERDE, <HI>and
Spani&s;h Soldiers.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>E$z.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well!&mdash;if &s;urrounded, we mu&s;t peri&s;h in
<PB N="75" REF="82">
the centre of them&mdash;Where do Rolla and Alonzo
hide their heads?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>ALONZO, ORANO,</HI> and Peruvians.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alonzo an&s;wers thee, and Alonzo's &s;word
&s;hall &s;peak for Rolla.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thou know'&s;t the advantage of thy num|bers.
&mdash;Thou dar'&s;t not &s;ingly face Pizarro.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Peruvians, &s;tir not a man!&mdash;Be this con|te&s;t
only our's.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Spaniards!&mdash;ob&s;erve ye the &s;ame.</P>
<STAGE>(Charge&punc;)</STAGE>
<P>They fight. <HI>Alonzo</HI>'s &s;hield is broken, and he is beat
down.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Piz.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now, traitor, to thy heart!</P>
<P>At this moment <HI>Elvira</HI> enters, habited as when <HI>Pizarro</HI>
fir&s;t beheld her.&mdash;<HI>Pizarro,</HI> appalled, &s;taggers back.
<HI>Alonzo</HI> renews the Fight, and &s;lays him.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Loud &s;houts from the Peruviaus.)</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>ATALIBA</HI> enters, and embraces <HI>ALONZO.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ata.</SPEAKER>
<P>My brave Alonzo!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alm.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alonzo, we &s;ubmit.&mdash;Spare us! we will
embark, and leave the coa&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Val.</SPEAKER>
<P>Elvira will confe&s;s I &s;av'd her life; &s;he has
&s;av'd thine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fear not. You are &s;afe.</P>
<STAGE>(Spaniards lay
down their arms.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Valverde &s;peaks the truth;&mdash;nor could he
think to meet me here.&mdash;An awful impul&s;e which
my &s;oul could not re&s;i&s;t, impell'd me hither.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Noble Elvira! my pre&s;erver! How can I
&s;peak what I, A$aliba, and his re&s;cued country,
owe to thee? If amid the&s;e grateful innocents thou
woud'&s;t remain&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="76" REF="83">
<SPEAKER>Elv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alonzo, no!&mdash;the de&s;tination of my future
life is fix'd. Humbled in penitence, I will endea|vour
to atone the guilty errors, which, however
ma&s;k'd by &s;hallow cheerfulne&s;s, have long con|&s;um'd
my &s;ecret heart.&mdash;When, by my &s;ufferings
purified, and penitence &s;incere, my &s;oul &s;hall dare
addre&s;s the Throne of Mercy in behalf of others,
&mdash;for thee, Alonzo; for thy Cora, and thy child;
for thee, thou virtuous Monarch, and the inno|cent
race you reign over, &s;hall Elvira's-prayers ad|dre&s;s
the God of Nature.&mdash;Valverde, you have
pre&s;erved my life. Cheri&s;h humanity&mdash;avoid the
foul examples thou ha&s;t view'd.&mdash;Spaniards return|ing
to your native home, a&s;&s;ure your rulers, they
mi&s;take the road to glory, or to power.&mdash;Tell them,
that the pur&s;uits of avarice, conque&s;t, and ambi|tion,
never yet made a people happy, or a nation
great.&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(Ca&s;ts a look of agony on the dead body of Pi|zarro
as &s;he pa&s;&s;es, and exit.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Flouri&s;h of Trumpets.)</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Valverde, Almagra,</HI> and Spani&s;h Soldiers, exeunt,
bearing off Pizarro's Body.&mdash;On a &s;ignal from
Alonzo, flouri&s;h of Mu&s;ic.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Alon.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ataliba! think not I wi&s;h to check the
voice of triumph&mdash;when I entreat we fir&s;t may
pay the tribute to our lov'd Rolla's memory.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>A &s;olemn March&mdash;Proce&s;&s;ion of Peruvian Soldiers,
bearing Rolla's Body on a Bier, &s;urrounded by Mi|litary
Trophies. The Prie&s;ts and Prie&s;te&s;&s;es at|tending
chaunt a Di$ge over the Bier.&mdash;Alonzo and
Cora kneel on either &s;ide of it, and ki&s;s Rolla's
hands in &s;ilent agony&mdash;In the looks of the King, and
of all pre&s;ent, the Triumph of the Day is lo&s;t, in
